Known Agenda gave trainer Todd Pletcher his record sixth Florida Derby. This has earned him an automatic stall for Kentucky. Soup and Sandwich (John Velaquez 3-1), put up a decent battle all-round the 1.1/8 mile contest, finishing 2.75 lengths behind. Greatest Honor and Nova Rags filled minor berths. Clocked stopped at 1:45:4/10. 

*** 

A sturdy bunch of cosmopolitan steeds from all corners of the globe,  were showcased on eight Dubai World Cup specialities, from Meydan in the United Arab Emirates on Saturday evening. But, the death of Dubai Golden Shaheen winner Zenden, who suffered a catastrophic front leg injury while galloping out past the finish of the six-furlong dirt race, left a real damper in everyone's heart. 






Lord North, ridden by Lanfranco Dettori, wins the $4m Turf race of Dubai World Cup at Meydan racecourse on March 27, 2021. 
Photo credit: Karim Sahib | AFP 

 

Zenden, 5, who was winning a graded/group race for the first time in his 15th career start, churned up a fabulous performance with help from Antonio Fresu, going immediately forward, then never rattled. He sustained the injury just after Antonio was thanking him with a cuddle. He stumbled and threw Antonio down, with no harm done. 

However, in the glittering Dubai World Cup, poor young Antonio was again dislodged from Military Law when he broke through the starting gate and ran off before being scratched. Talk about bitter sweetness, or, adding insult to injury. 

*** 

France's, Deryan (Loritz Mendizabal 3-1), broke the track record lifting the US$750,000 Dubai Kahayla Classic Sponsored by Mubadala, in 2:11:8/10. Conditioner, Didier Guillemin also won the Al Quoz Sprint with the Right Man way back in 2017, at Meydan. Owned and bred by Sheikh Mansour bin Zayed Al Nayan, Dreyan joins his other Rabbah De Carrere, who started the trend.  Point being, any horse that wins on this occasion, has to be brilliant, as competition is mesmerising, 



